article.description: DeWanna Bonner scored 25 points and Auburn (No. 6 ESPN/USA Today, No. 7 AP) clinched its first SEC title in 20 years with a 94-57 win over Arkansas on Sunday.
article.headline: Bonner scores 25 as No. 6 Tigers finish season 12-0 at home
article.linkText: No. 6 Auburn routs Arkansas, clinches SEC title
article.story:
AUBURN, Ala. -- Auburn (No. 6 ESPN/USA Today, No. 7 AP) ended a 20-year SEC title drought with 20 minutes of nearly flawless play.

DeWanna Bonner scored 25 points and the Tigers raced to a 22-point lead with a turnover-free first half on their way a 94-57 win over Arkansas in Sunday's regular-season finale, the most lopsided league matchup of the season.

The second half was just a buildup to the celebration.

"That was just some really good basketball," said Auburn coach Nell Fortner, a cut-down net draped around her neck. "I thought we were very focused and very disciplined with what we were doing. It's the way you want to be playing at this time in the season."

The Tigers (27-2, 12-2 Southeastern Conference) made sure they didn't have to hope for a Vanderbilt loss to Tennessee later in the day to claim the outright championship.

Bonner made 10-of-11 free throws in her final regular-season game. Sherell Hobbs added 18 points -- 16 in the first half -- and Whitney Boddie had 10 points and eight assists in their home finales. Freshman Chantel Hilliard scored 11 points.

The Tigers finished 12-0 at home this season and captured the top seed for the league tournament at North Little Rock, Ark. They open Friday against the Arkansas-Mississippi winner hoping to secure a No. 1 seed in the NCAA tournament.

"I'm just thrilled for this team and this program," Fortner said. "It's absolutely what our goal has been since we took this job: to win this championship and then to have an opportunity to compete for the national championship. And that's what we're on our way to do."

Fortner isn't sure what her team has to do in the SEC tournament to earn a top seed. She knows the best way to make a strong argument.

"If we won it, I think that we would definitely put ourselves in a good position to get a 1 seed," she said.

Whitney Jones led Arkansas (17-12, 6-8) with 23 points.

Auburn equaled the most points scored in an SEC game this season and had the widest victory margin. Florida also scored 94 against the Razorbacks on Feb. 1 while two other SEC games were decided by 30 points..

The Tigers built a 54-32 halftime lead after shooting 53 percent and forcing 11 turnovers without committing one. Auburn had only six turnovers and forced 21.

"Auburn had 11 assists and zero turnovers in the first half, so they played near perfection," Arkansas coach Tom Collen said. "They're the SEC champs. They deserve to be. They're the best team in our conference right now and you've got to give them all the credit in the world."

The Razorbacks couldn't come any closer than 17 in the second half, even with Fortner resting all five starters for a long stretch.

"We just kind of came out and took it to them from the beginning, kind of put them back on their heels," Bonner said.

It was the final home game for seniors Bonner, Boddie, Hobbs and Trevesha Jackson. They were honored afterward with highlight reels of careers that helped turn around the Tigers' program playing on the scoreboard video screen. Jackson added seven points and 11 rebounds.

"They came in here with a brand-new staff and believed in what we were telling them," Fortner said. "That was the biggest thing. I'll always be grateful to them for that and for getting this program back where it needs to be."

Bonner, meanwhile, moved within 18 points of Becky Jackson's school career mark of 2,068 points. She hit the team's only 3-pointer in the final minutes when Fortner put the seniors back in briefly before letting them each exit a final time to standing ovations.

"I'm really focused on the SEC championships," Bonner said. "Yeah, we're seniors, but we're not done yet."
